Use Case Scenario¶

Title: Capacity Forecasting and Strategic Insights for Bars, Pubs, Cafes, and Restaurants in Melbourne

As a data scientist working with the Melbourne City Planning Department,

I want to analyze historical and real-time data on seating capacities and patron trends within Melbourne’s bars, pubs, cafes, and restaurants,

So that I can identify patterns, predict future capacity requirements, and highlight key areas for potential growth and new hospitality establishments.

This will help inform strategic decisions related to zoning, licensing, and infrastructure development to accommodate the city’s evolving hospitality demands. These insights will enhance customer experiences, support business owners, and drive Melbourne's economic growth by ensuring a thriving and balanced hospitality sector.

By leveraging predictive models and conducting thorough capacity analysis, I aim to deliver actionable insights that will aid in strategic planning, allowing the city to adapt to future needs while fostering sustainable growth within Melbourne’s hospitality ecosystem.

Project Goal: Capacity Forecasting and Strategic Insights for Bars, Pubs, Cafes, and Restaurants in Melbourne

Conduct an in-depth analysis of the relationship between the seating capacity of cafes and restaurants and their location within Melbourne. This study aims to develop predictive models that estimate potential seating capacity based on geographic and demographic factors. The ultimate goal is to provide evidence-based recommendations to cafe and restaurant owners for optimizing operations, including location selection, seating arrangement, and marketing strategies. Additionally, the project will offer insights to urban planners to enhance the hospitality landscape in Melbourne, contributing to a more vibrant and economically thriving city.

Key Activities

  • Data Integration: Combine data from the "Cafes and Restaurants with Seating Capacity" dataset with relevant demographic and geographic data to create a comprehensive dataset for analysis.
  • Data Preprocessing: Clean and preprocess the combined dataset to ensure accuracy and relevance for analysis.
  • Exploratory Data Analysis: Perform exploratory data analysis to understand the relationships and patterns within the data.
  • Predictive Modeling: Develop and validate predictive models to estimate seating capacity based on geographic and demographic factors.
  • Visualization and Reporting: Create visualizations and reports to present key findings and recommendations to stakeholders.

Expected Outcome

A comprehensive report detailing the relationship between geographic/demographic factors and the seating capacity of cafes and restaurants in Melbourne, with actionable recommendations for optimizing operations. The report will also provide insights for urban planners to enhance Melbourne's hospitality landscape.

Impact

This project will empower cafe and restaurant owners to make data-driven decisions, improving operational efficiency and enhancing customer experiences. Urban planners will benefit from insights that support sustainable development and a vibrant hospitality sector in Melbourne, contributing to the city's economic and social vitality.

Dataset Import Through API¶

In [3]:
#Function to collect data
def collect_data(dataset_id):
    base_url = 'https://data.melbourne.vic.gov.au/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/'
    #apikey = api_key #use if use datasets API_key permissions
    dataset_id = dataset_id
    format = 'csv'

    url = f'{base_url}{dataset_id}/exports/{format}'
    params = {
        'select': '*',
        'limit': -1,  # all records
        'lang': 'en',
        'timezone': 'UTC',
        #'api_key': apikey  #use if use datasets API_key permissions
    }

    # GET request
    response = requests.get(url, params=params)

    if response.status_code == 200:
        # StringIO to read the CSV data
        url_content = response.content.decode('utf-8')
        dataset = pd.read_csv(StringIO(url_content), delimiter=';')
        return dataset
    else:
        print(f'Request failed with status code {response.status_code}')

Handle Missing Values in Cafes and Restaurants Dataset¶

In [12]:
# Step 1: Create a mapping of 'building_address' to the most common 'location'
address_to_location_map = cafes_restaurants_updated.groupby('building_address')['location'].agg(lambda x: x.mode().iloc[0] if not x.mode().empty else None)

# Step 2: Fill missing 'location' values using the mapping
cafes_restaurants_updated['location'] = cafes_restaurants_updated.apply(
    lambda row: address_to_location_map[row['building_address']] if pd.isnull(row['location']) else row['location'],
    axis=1
)

# Verify if the missing values are filled
missing_values_after_filling = cafes_restaurants_updated['location'].isnull().sum()
print(f"Missing values in 'location' after filling: {missing_values_after_filling}")

# Define the interactive map function
def update_map_bars(trading_name):
    clear_output(wait=True)
    melbourne_map = folium.Map(location=[-37.8136, 144.9631], zoom_start=12)
    marker_cluster = MarkerCluster().add_to(melbourne_map)
    
    if trading_name == "All Locations":
        for idx, row in gdf_bars_pubs.iterrows():
            folium.CircleMarker(
                location=[row.geometry.y, row.geometry.x],
                radius=3,
                color='blue',
                fill=True,
                fill_color='blue',
                popup=f"Trading Name: {row['trading_name']}, Patrons: {row['number_of_patrons']}"
            ).add_to(marker_cluster)
    else:
        selected_gdf = gdf_bars_pubs[gdf_bars_pubs['trading_name'] == trading_name]
        for idx, row in selected_gdf.iterrows():
            folium.CircleMarker(
                location=[row.geometry.y, row.geometry.x],
                radius=8,
                color='red',
                fill=True,
                fill_color='red',
                popup=f"Trading Name: {row['trading_name']}, Patrons: {row['number_of_patrons']}"
            ).add_to(marker_cluster)
    
    display(melbourne_map)

# Create the dropdown widget
trading_name_dropdown_bars = widgets.Dropdown(

    description='Select Bar/Pub:'
)

# Link the dropdown to the map update function

# Function to update the map based on dropdown selection
def update_map(trading_name):
    # Clear the previous output
    clear_output(wait=True)
    
    # Create the map
    if trading_name == "All Locations":
        updated_map = folium.Map(location=[-37.8136, 144.9631], zoom_start=12)
        for _, row in merged_df.iterrows():
            location = [float(coord) for coord in row['location_bars'].split(', ')]
            popup_text = f"{row['trading_name_bars']}: Seats {row['number_of_seats']}, Patrons {row['number_of_patrons']}"
            folium.Marker(
                location=location,
                popup=popup_text,
                tooltip=row['trading_name_bars']
            ).add_to(updated_map)
    else:
        selected_row = merged_df[merged_df['trading_name_bars'] == trading_name].iloc[0]
        location = [float(coord) for coord in selected_row['location_bars'].split(', ')]
        popup_text = f"{selected_row['trading_name_bars']}: Seats {selected_row['number_of_seats']}, Patrons {selected_row['number_of_patrons']}"
        updated_map = folium.Map(location=location, zoom_start=15)
        folium.Marker(
            location=location,
            popup=popup_text,
            tooltip=selected_row['trading_name_bars']
        ).add_to(updated_map)
    
    # Display the updated map
    display(updated_map)

def predict_future_capacity_combined(bars_model, cafes_model, bars_dataset, cafes_dataset, property_id, years_to_predict=5, start_year=2024):
    # Check if property_id exists in Bars and Pubs dataset
    in_bars = not bars_dataset[bars_dataset['property_id'] == property_id].empty
    # Check if property_id exists in Cafes and Restaurants dataset
    in_cafes = not cafes_dataset[cafes_dataset['property_id'] == property_id].empty
    
    if not in_bars and not in_cafes:
        print(f"No data found for property_id: {property_id} in either dataset.")
        return

    if in_bars:
        # Get trading name from Bars and Pubs dataset
        trading_name_bars = bars_dataset[bars_dataset['property_id'] == property_id]['trading_name'].values[0]
        print(f"\nProperty ID {property_id} ({trading_name_bars}) found in Bars and Pubs dataset:")
        predict_future_capacity(bars_model, bars_dataset, property_id, 'number_of_patrons', years_to_predict)

    if in_cafes:
        # Get trading name from Cafes and Restaurants dataset
        trading_name_cafes = cafes_dataset[cafes_dataset['property_id'] == property_id]['trading_name'].values[0]
        print(f"\nProperty ID {property_id} ({trading_name_cafes}) found in Cafes and Restaurants dataset:")
        predict_future_capacity(cafes_model, cafes_dataset, property_id, 'number_of_seats', years_to_predict)

# Function for predicting future capacities for a specific property
def predict_future_capacity(model, dataset, property_id, target_column, years_to_predict=5, start_year=2024):
    # Filter data for the specific property_id
    property_data = dataset[dataset['property_id'] == property_id].copy()

    if property_data.empty:
        print(f"No data found for property_id: {property_id}")
        return

    # Prepare future years (2024-2028)
    future_years = pd.DataFrame({
        'census_year': [start_year + i for i in range(0, years_to_predict)],
        'property_id': [property_id] * years_to_predict
    })

    # Make predictions for future years
    predictions = model.predict(future_years[['census_year', 'property_id']])
    predictions = pd.Series(predictions).round().astype(int)

    # Combine predictions with future years and print them
    future_years[target_column] = predictions
    print(f"Predicted {target_column} for property_id {property_id} for the years {start_year} to {start_year + years_to_predict - 1}:")
    print(future_years[['census_year', target_column]].to_string(index=False))
    
    return future_years[['census_year', target_column]]

# Example usage
property_id_input = input("Enter the Property ID to predict seating and patron capacities: ")
predict_future_capacity_combined(rf_bars, rf_cafes, bars_pubs_sorted, cafes_restaurants_sorted, int(property_id_input))

Random Forest Model to Predict Patron and Seating Capacities¶

Data Preprocessing and Feature Engineering¶

  1. Grouping and Sorting: The data is grouped by property_id and sorted by census_year to establish the historical trends in seating and patron capacities.
  2. Handle Missing Values: Missing values are imputed using a forward fill method to ensure no gaps in the time series data.
  3. Feature Engineering: New time-based features are created by calculating the difference in capacity from the previous year (capacity_change), adding more predictive power to the model.

Model Training¶

A Random Forest model is used to predict the seating capacities for cafes/restaurants and the patron capacities for bars/pubs.

Key Steps:¶

  1. Feature and Target Selection: The model uses features like census_year and property_id, while targets are the total number_of_seats for cafes/restaurants and number_of_patrons for bars/pubs.
  2. Train/Test Split: The data is split into 80% for training and 20% for testing.
  3. Model Training: Two separate Random Forest models are trained — one for cafes/restaurants and one for bars/pubs, using n_estimators=100 for both.
  4. Evaluation: The model's performance is evaluated using Mean Squared Error (MSE), with results:
    • Bars and Pubs MSE: 75817.1159
    • Cafes and Restaurants MSE: 16412.2327

Prediction for Future Years (2024-2028)¶

The model is used to forecast the seating and patron capacities for a selected property_id over the next 5 years (2024-2028).

Key Steps:¶

  1. Future Years Generation: A DataFrame is created for future years from 2024 to 2028.
  2. Prediction Function: A function predict_future_capacity_combined generates the predictions for seating and patron capacities for a specific property_id.
  3. Example: After entering a property_id, the model outputs the predicted seating and patron capacities for the specified future years.

This workflow allows for strategic planning based on expected future capacities in both cafes/restaurants and bars/pubs.

Comprehensive Conclusion for Capacity Forecasting and Strategic Insights for Bars, Pubs, Cafes, and Restaurants in Melbourne¶

This project, titled Capacity Forecasting and Strategic Insights for Bars, Pubs, Cafes, and Restaurants in Melbourne, focused on analyzing seating and patron capacities in Melbourne’s bars, pubs, cafes, and restaurants. By integrating data on seating capacities with demographic and geographic variables, we aimed to provide actionable insights to both business owners and city planners. The project followed a structured approach of data integration, preprocessing, exploratory analysis, predictive modeling, and reporting.

Key Findings:¶

  1. Seating Capacity Trends:

    • The exploratory data analysis revealed clear trends in seating capacities across different areas in Melbourne, with higher capacities concentrated in the central business district and popular hospitality hubs.
    • Locations like Docklands and South Wharf emerged as high-capacity zones, making them ideal hotspots for new establishments.
    • The visualizations provided insights into the distribution of seating types (indoor vs. outdoor), which varied significantly by industry and geographic area.

  2. Predictive Modeling:

    • Using both time series forecasting and Random Forest models, we predicted seating and patron capacities for the next five years (2024-2028).
    • The ARIMA models demonstrated stable predictions for specific property IDs, allowing stakeholders to anticipate future demand.
    • The Random Forest models provided reasonably accurate predictions for both seating and patron capacities. The MSE for bars/pubs was 75817.12, while cafes/restaurants had an MSE of 16412.23. These results indicate that the model performed well given the complexity of the data and its many influencing factors.

  3. High Capacity and Low Competition Zones:

    • The analysis successfully identified key locations in Melbourne where high seating capacity intersects with low competition, providing strategic insights for potential new entrants to the market.
    • Visualizations of seating capacities by location helped pinpoint areas where businesses could potentially thrive due to lower competition yet sufficient seating demand.

  4. Interactive Mapping:

    • The use of interactive maps, particularly through Folium, allowed stakeholders to visualize seating and patron capacities geographically. This functionality provided a user-friendly interface for urban planners and business owners to identify gaps and opportunities in the hospitality sector.
    • By layering additional filters like seating capacity and number of businesses, users can make informed decisions about new locations or expansions.

Business and Urban Planning Recommendations:¶

  • Business Owners:

    • Businesses looking to establish new cafes or restaurants should consider locations with high seating demand and lower competition, such as areas identified in Docklands and parts of the CBD.
    • Optimizing seating arrangements (e.g., balancing indoor and outdoor seating) based on geographic and demographic insights can enhance customer satisfaction and operational efficiency.
    • Predictive models suggest stable growth in seating capacity demand, particularly in high-traffic areas, providing confidence for businesses to expand.

  • Urban Planners:

    • The predictive analysis highlights hotspots where zoning and licensing regulations might need to adapt to growing hospitality demand. By preparing infrastructure in these high-demand areas, the city can ensure it meets the needs of a growing population.
    • Planning for future seating capacity expansions based on projected trends can help maintain a balanced, vibrant hospitality sector that contributes to the city’s economic and social vitality.

Final Impact:¶

This project provides valuable insights into the dynamics of Melbourne’s hospitality sector, contributing to data-driven decision-making for both business owners and urban planners. By anticipating future capacity needs and identifying key hotspots for growth, Melbourne can foster a thriving hospitality ecosystem that promotes economic growth and enhances the overall customer experience.

Moving forward, this predictive framework can be extended to include more detailed demographic data and broader geographic coverage, allowing for even more granular predictions and strategic planning recommendations.
